body:
Hi @gsmet 

I tried your fix with a project with submodules. The project follows a hexagonal architecture and is modelled the following way.

```
project root
|
| - application core with only a few dependencies
| - AWS & Quarkus stuff, API client for external services, etc.
| - integration tests
| - AWS lambdas domain A
| - AWS lambdas domain B
| - AWS lambdas domain C
...
```

Test coverage has fallen from around 85% to 60%. The decrease in coverage seems to be due to the fact that most classes in the `AWS & Quarkus stuff, API client for external services, etc` module are tested in the `integration tests` module and not in the module itself. 

When looking at the Jacoco project, I noticed in particular that the coverage there has fallen sharply, often even to 0%. This could probably be due to the fact that the classes from the other module are no longer taken into account.

Would it even be possible to distinguish between classes from the application itself and external libraries in such a project structure?

I then tried a "brute force" approach and changed the affected lines to.

```
    try {
        byte[] enhanced = instrumenter.instrument(bytes, className);
        if (enhanced == null) {
            return bytes;
        }
        return enhanced;
    } catch (IOException e) {
        LOG.warnf(e,
            "Unable to instrument class %s with Jacoco, keeping the original class",
            className);
        return bytes;
    }
```

The build was successful and the coverage was also at the same level as before. Of course, this is not a nice approach, but at least the build is not blocked and the coverage is calculated correctly.
